=========================================
C++14 BINARY LITERALS (0b)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What are Binary Literals?

Binary Literals were introduced in C++14.

They allow integer constants to be written directly in binary form using the prefix

0b

or

0B

Syntax

0bBinaryDigits

Example

int x = 0b1010;

-----------------------------------------

2. Why were Binary Literals introduced?

Before C++14, C++ had

Decimal

int x = 10;

Octal

int x = 012;

Hexadecimal

int x = 0xA;

But there was NO way to write binary numbers directly.

C++14 solved this by introducing

0b

-----------------------------------------

3. Example

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 0b1010;

    cout << x;

    return 0;
}

Output

10

-----------------------------------------

4. How does Binary Literal work?

Example

0b1010

Calculation

1 × 2³ = 8

0 × 2² = 0

1 × 2¹ = 2

0 × 2⁰ = 0

Total

8 + 2 = 10

Therefore

0b1010

equals

10

-----------------------------------------

5. More Examples

0b1        = 1

0b10       = 2

0b11       = 3

0b100      = 4

0b101      = 5

0b1111     = 15

0b10000    = 16

0b100000   = 32

-----------------------------------------

