13. Interview Questions

Q. What are Binary Literals?

Answer

Binary Literals were introduced in C++14. They allow integer constants to be written directly in binary form using the prefix 0b or 0B.

Example

int x = 0b1010;

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why were Binary Literals introduced?

Answer

They improve the readability of code involving bit manipulation, bit masks, flags, 
and low-level programming by allowing developers to write binary values directly instead of converting them to decimal or hexadecimal.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Where are Binary Literals commonly used?

Answer

• Bit manipulation
• Bit masks
• Flags
• Embedded systems
• Networking
• Device drivers
• Operating systems

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced Binary Literals?

Answer

C++14

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is the difference between

10

and

0b1010 ?

Answer

Both represent the same integer value (10).

The difference is only the notation in the source code. Binary literals make the bit pattern easier for humans to understand.

